GIT-INJECT(1)                     Git Manual                      GIT-INJECT(1)


NAME
       git-inject - Merge changes into an older commit


SYNOPSIS
       git inject <target> [<patch>]
       git inject [<target>] --staged
       git inject [<target>] --file <file>...
       git inject (--continue | --abort | --revert | --clear)


DESCRIPTION
       `git inject` performs an automatic `git rebase` operation to remove
       the patch commit from the history on the current branch, then apply
       the patch diffs to the target commit. Any changes in the current
       branch that are not committed to history are saved to a temporary
       area (unless `--staged` option is supplied to the command) and
       restored upon successful completion of the injection process.

       `git-inject` is best suited for shallow fixes and patchwork in
       commits on local repositories and personal branches where the others
       are not basing their work and quick cleaning of commits in the git
       tree before pushing upstream.

       A target commit is either supplied or assumed. If only `<target>`
       is specified, the current `HEAD` commit is used as the value of
       the patch.

       It is possible that a merge failure will prevent this process from
       being completely automatic. You will have to resolve any such merge
       failure and run `git inject --continue`.

       To check out the original `HEAD` and remove the `.git/INJECT_STATE/`
       working files, use the command `git inject --abort` instead.


INSTALLATION
       Clone the repository and then run the installation script for your
       operating system.

       Windows:

           powershell.exe -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\install.ps1

       Linux/macOS:

           chmod +x install.sh
           ./install.sh


OPTIONS
       <target>
              The older commit that receives the changes. This commit
              must be a direct ancestor of the `<patch>` commit.

       <patch>
              The newer commit containing the changes to merge. If the
              patch commit is on the same branch where the injection was
              started, the commit is removed from the branch history
              during injection.

       -s
       --staged
              Inject all changes in the index (staging area) into the
              specified target.

       --is-empty
              Allow the creation of an empty commit if the patch contains
              no changes or if the changes are already present in the
              target history.

       --into <target>
              Syntactic sugar for positional placement. Inject the patch
              commit into the specified target. Does not alter script
              operation.


SANDBOX
       To create a temporary sandbox to test the command, clone the
       repository then run

           chmod +x ./test/sandbox
           ./test/sandbox setup

       and navigate to the generated 'git-inject-sandbox/' folder and open
       the git project.

       The sandbox is crated with six branches, two of which are orphan
       branches and the other four are split between the orphans, two each.
       The included files are designed to be distinguishable from each
       other by file extension.

       Here's what the tree structure would look like:

           * 82f1807 (feature)           * 6cf071b (reference)
           | * 6c0b3b1 (topic)           | * 41d729a (article)
           | | * b4afe1c (master)        | | * 6316505 (docs)
           | |/                          | |/
           |/|                           |/|
           * | d08a371                   * | 02a7b8f
           |/                            |/
           * 34252d6                     * b6d343a

       The tree is truncated to cut down unnecessary empty space.


